docs.abstract: The president, who has made racial equity and justice central themes of his administration, was in Tulsa, Okla., to commemorate a painful part of the country’s history.
docs.snippet: The president, who has made racial equity and justice central themes of his administration, was in Tulsa, Okla., to commemorate a painful part of the country’s history.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A century after a white mob destroyed a vibrant African American community in Tulsa, Okla., torching hundreds of homes and indiscriminately shooting people in the streets, President Biden told a crowd of survivors and their families that the story of the massacre “will be known in full view.”

headline.main: Biden Promises Tulsa Massacre Survivors Their Story Will Be ‘Known in Full View’
headline.print_headline: In Tulsa, President Tells Of a Massacre’s Horrors

docs.abstract: Police officers at the University of Washington in Seattle, regarded as one of the nation’s most progressive cities, said they were the target of racist insults and harassment.
docs.snippet: Police officers at the University of Washington in Seattle, regarded as one of the nation’s most progressive cities, said they were the target of racist insults and harassment.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Earlier this year, as Officer Russell Ellis neared the end of his late shift at the University of Washington’s campus police department, one of his superiors offered him an energy drink. The sergeant was laughing, Mr. Ellis said, noting that the beverage was flavored like watermelon.

headline.main: Black Campus Police Officers Say They Suffered ‘Unbearable’ Racism
headline.print_headline: Campus Officers File $8 Million Racism Claim

docs.abstract: As visitors trickle back into the city after a heavy year, walking tours and other experiences that emphasize seldom-told stories about local life and history are taking on new resonance.
docs.snippet: As visitors trickle back into the city after a heavy year, walking tours and other experiences that emphasize seldom-told stories about local life and history are taking on new resonance.
docs.lead_paragraph: As the second-most visited city in the world (that is, prepandemic), Paris has always meant brisk business when it comes to guided tours and excursions for travelers. From historical walks and cooking classes to outings that grant exclusive access to artists’ workshops, museum archives and private mansions, there are activities for almost any interest.

headline.main: Specialized Experiences Offer Fresh Looks on Paris

docs.abstract: In Tuesday's primary for mayor of New York City, Democrats have a choice between two distinctly different paths on policing, crime and civil rights.
docs.snippet: In Tuesday's primary for mayor of New York City, Democrats have a choice between two distinctly different paths on policing, crime and civil rights.
docs.lead_paragraph: An urgent debate is playing out right now in the Democratic Party about policing as cities see sharp rises in violent crime. The fight to control that disorder is also a battle for the direction of the party — do police departments need more resources to fight crime? Do they need to be restrained, given a long record of abuses and policies like stop-and-frisk? How do the police earn more trust from Black and brown residents? Which tactics are right, and which tactics violate our rights?

headline.main: He’s a Former Officer. She’s ‘Had Enough’ of the Police. Who Will Come Out Ahead?
headline.print_headline: City’s Election Could Set Agenda on Policing
